\id PSA
\mt3 THE BOOK OF
\mt1 PSALMS
\b 
\ms1 Book I
\c 1
\cl PSALM 1
\p
\v 1 ¶ Blessed \add is\add* the man that walketh not in the counsel of the ungodly, nor standeth in the way of sinners, nor sitteth in the seat of the scornful.
\p
\v 2 But his delight \add is\add* in the law of the LORD; and in his law doth he meditate day and night.
\p
\v 3 And he shall be like a tree planted by the rivers of water, that bringeth forth its fruit in its season; his leaf also shall not wither; and whatsoever he doeth shall prosper.
\p
\v 4 The ungodly \add are\add* not so: but \add are\add* like the chaff which the wind driveth away.
\p
\v 5 Therefore the ungodly shall not stand in the judgment, nor sinners in the congregation of the righteous.
\p
\v 6 For the LORD knoweth the way of the righteous: but the way of the ungodly shall perish.
\c 2
\cl PSALM 2
\p
\v 1 ¶ Why do the nations rage, and the peoples imagine a vain thing?
\p
\v 2 The kings of the earth set themselves, and the rulers take counsel together, against the LORD, and against his anointed, \add saying,\add*
\p
\v 3 Let us break their bands asunder, and cast away their cords from us.
\p
\v 4 He that sitteth in the heavens shall laugh: the Lord shall have them in derision.
\p
\v 5 Then shall he speak unto them in his wrath, and vex them in his sore displeasure.
\p
\v 6 Yet have I set my king upon my holy hill of Zion.
\p
\v 7 I will declare the decree: the LORD hath said unto me, Thou \add art\add* my Son; this day have I begotten thee.
\p
\v 8 Ask of me, and I shall give \add thee\add* the nations \add for\add* thine inheritance, and the uttermost parts of the earth \add for\add* thy possession.
\p
\v 9 Thou shalt break them with a rod of iron; thou shalt dash them in pieces like a potter’s vessel.
\p
\v 10 Be wise now therefore, O ye kings: be instructed, ye judges of the earth.
\p
\v 11 Serve the LORD with fear, and rejoice with trembling.
\p
\v 12 Kiss the Son, lest he be angry, and ye perish \add from\add* the way, when his wrath is kindled but a little. Blessed \add are\add* all they that put their trust in him.
\c 3
\cl PSALM 3
\d A Psalm of David, when he fled from Absalom his son.
\p
\v 1 ¶ LORD, how are they increased that trouble me! many \add are\add* they that rise up against me.
\p
\v 2 Many \add there be\add* that say of my soul, \add There is\add* no help for him in God. Selah.
\p
\v 3 But thou, O LORD, \add art\add* a shield for me; my glory, and the lifter up of mine head.
\p
\v 4 I cried unto the LORD with my voice, and he heard me out of his holy hill. Selah.
\p
\v 5 I laid me down and slept; I awaked; for the LORD sustained me.
\p
\v 6 I will not be afraid of ten thousands of people, that have set \add themselves\add* against me round about.
\p
\v 7 Arise, O LORD; save me, O my God: for thou hast smitten all mine enemies \add upon\add* the cheek bone; thou hast broken the teeth of the ungodly.
\p
\v 8 Salvation \add belongeth\add* unto the LORD: thy blessing \add is\add* upon thy people. Selah.
\c 4
\cl PSALM 4
\d To the chief Musician on Neginoth, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ Hear me when I call, O God of my righteousness: thou hast enlarged me \add when I was\add* in distress; have mercy upon me, and hear my prayer.
\p
\v 2 O ye sons of men, how long \add will ye turn\add* my glory into shame? \add how long\add* will ye love vanity, \add and\add* seek after lies? Selah.
\p
\v 3 But know that the LORD hath set apart him that is godly for himself: the LORD will hear when I call unto him.
\p
\v 4 Stand in awe, and sin not: commune with your own heart upon your bed, and be still. Selah.
\p
\v 5 Offer the sacrifices of righteousness, and put your trust in the LORD.
\p
\v 6 \add There be\add* many that say, Who will show us \add any\add* good? LORD, lift thou up the light of thy countenance upon us.
\p
\v 7 Thou hast put gladness in my heart, more than in the time \add that\add* their corn and their wine increased.
\p
\v 8 I will both lay me down in peace, and sleep: for thou, LORD, only makest me dwell in safety.
\c 5
\cl PSALM 5
\d To the chief Musician upon Nehiloth, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ Give ear to my words, O LORD, consider my meditation.
\p
\v 2 Hearken unto the voice of my cry, my King, and my God: for unto thee will I pray.
\p
\v 3 My voice shalt thou hear in the morning, O LORD; in the morning will I direct \add my prayer\add* unto thee, and will look up.
\p
\v 4 For thou \add art\add* not a God that hath pleasure in wickedness: neither shall evil dwell with thee.
\p
\v 5 The foolish shall not stand in thy sight: thou hatest all workers of iniquity.
\p
\v 6 Thou shalt destroy them that speak lies: the LORD will abhor the bloody and deceitful man.
\p
\v 7 But as for me, I will come \add into\add* thy house in the multitude of thy mercy: \add and\add* in thy fear will I worship toward thy holy temple.
\p
\v 8 Lead me, O LORD, in thy righteousness because of mine enemies; make thy way straight before my face.
\p
\v 9 For \add there is\add* no faithfulness in their mouth; their inward part \add is\add* very wickedness; their throat \add is\add* an open sepulchre; they flatter with their tongue.
\p
\v 10 Hold them not guiltless, O God; let them fall by their own counsels; cast them out in the multitude of their transgressions; for they have rebelled against thee.
\p
\v 11 But let all those that put their trust in thee rejoice: let them ever shout for joy, because thou defendest them: let them also that love thy name be joyful in thee.
\p
\v 12 For thou, LORD, wilt bless the righteous; with favour wilt thou compass him as \add with\add* a shield.
\c 6
\cl PSALM 6
\d To the chief Musician on Neginoth upon Sheminith, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ O LORD, rebuke me not in thine anger, neither chasten me in thy hot displeasure.
\p
\v 2 Have mercy upon me, O LORD; for I \add am\add* weak: O LORD, heal me; for my bones are vexed.
\p
\v 3 My soul is also sore vexed: but thou, O LORD, how long?
\p
\v 4 Return, O LORD, deliver my soul: oh save me for thy mercies’ sake.
\p
\v 5 For in death \add there is\add* no remembrance of thee: in the grave who shall give thee thanks?
\p
\v 6 I am weary with my groaning; all the night make I my bed to swim; I water my couch with my tears.
\p
\v 7 Mine eye is consumed because of grief; it waxeth old because of all mine enemies.
\p
\v 8 Depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity; for the LORD hath heard the voice of my weeping.
\p 
\v 9 The LORD hath heard my supplication; the LORD will receive my prayer.
\p 
\v 10 Let all mine enemies be ashamed and sore vexed: let them return \add and\add* be ashamed suddenly.
\c 7
\cl PSALM 7
\d Shiggaion of David, which he sang unto the LORD, concerning the words of Cush the Benjamite.
\p
\v 1 ¶ O Lord my God, in thee do I put my trust: save me from all them that persecute me, and deliver me:
\p
\v 2 Lest he tear my soul like a lion, rending \add it\add* in pieces, while \add there is\add* none to deliver.
\p
\v 3 O LORD my God, if I have done this; if there be iniquity in my hands;
\p 
\v 4 If I have rewarded evil unto him that was at peace with me; (yea, I have delivered him that without cause is mine enemy:)
\p
\v 5 Let the enemy persecute my soul, and take \add it;\add* yea, let him tread down my life upon the earth, and lay mine honour in the dust. Selah.
\p
\v 6 Arise, O LORD, in thine anger, lift up thyself because of the rage of mine enemies: and awake for me \add to\add* the judgment \add that\add* thou hast commanded.
\p
\v 7 So shall the congregation of the peoples compass thee about: for their sakes therefore return thou on high.
\p
\v 8 The LORD shall judge the peoples: judge me, O LORD, according to my righteousness, and according to mine integrity \add that is\add* in me.
\p
\v 9 Oh let the wickedness of the wicked come to an end; but establish the just: for the righteous God trieth the hearts and reins.
\p
\v 10 My defence \add is\add* of God, who saveth the upright in heart.
\p
\v 11 God judgeth the righteous, and God is angry \add with the wicked\add* every day.
\p
\v 12 If he turn not, he will whet his sword; he hath bent his bow, and made it ready.
\p
\v 13 He hath also prepared for him the instruments of death; he ordaineth his arrows against the persecutors.
\p
\v 14 Behold, he travaileth with iniquity, and hath conceived mischief, and brought forth falsehood.
\p
\v 15 He made a pit, and digged it, and is fallen into the ditch \add which\add* he made.
\p
\v 16 His mischief shall return upon his own head, and his violent dealing shall come down upon his own pate.
\p
\v 17 I will praise the LORD according to his righteousness: and will sing praise to the name of the LORD most high.
\c 8
\cl PSALM 8
\d To the chief Musician upon Gittith, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ O LORD our Lord, how excellent \add is\add* thy name in all the earth! who hast set thy glory above the heavens.
\p
\v 2 Out of the mouth of babes and sucklings hast thou ordained strength because of thine enemies, that thou mightest still the enemy and the avenger.
\p
\v 3 When I consider thy heavens, the work of thy fingers, the moon and the stars, which thou hast ordained;
\p
\v 4 What is man, that thou art mindful of him? and the son of man, that thou visitest him?
\p
\v 5 For thou hast made him a little lower than the angels, and hast crowned him with glory and honour.
\p
\v 6 Thou madest him to have dominion over the works of thy hands; thou hast put all \add things\add* under his feet:
\p
\v 7 All sheep and oxen, yea, and the beasts of the field;
\p
\v 8 The fowl of the air, and the fish of the sea, \add and whatsoever\add* passeth through the paths of the seas.
\p
\v 9 O LORD our Lord, how excellent is thy name in all the earth!
\c 9
\cl PSALM 9
\d To the chief Musician upon Muthlabben, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ I will praise \add thee,\add* O LORD, with my whole heart; I will show forth all thy marvellous works.
\p
\v 2 I will be glad and rejoice in thee: I will sing praise to thy name, O thou most High.
\p
\v 3 When mine enemies are turned back, they shall fall and perish at thy presence.
\p
\v 4 For thou hast maintained my right and my cause; thou satest in the throne judging right.
\p
\v 5 Thou hast rebuked the nations, thou hast destroyed the wicked, thou hast put out their name for ever and ever.
\p
\v 6 O thou enemy, destructions are come to a perpetual end: and thou hast destroyed cities; their memorial is perished with them.
\p
\v 7 But the LORD shall endure for ever: he hath prepared his throne for judgment.
\p
\v 8 And he shall judge the world in righteousness, he shall minister judgment to the peoples in uprightness.
\p
\v 9 The LORD also will be a refuge for the oppressed, a refuge in times of trouble.
\p
\v 10 And they that know thy name will put their trust in thee: for thou, LORD, hast not forsaken them that seek thee.
\p
\v 11 Sing praises to the LORD, who dwelleth in Zion: declare among the peoples his doings.
\p
\v 12 When he maketh inquisition for blood, he remembereth them: he forgetteth not the cry of the humble.
\p
\v 13 Have mercy upon me, O LORD; consider my affliction \add which I suffer\add* of them that hate me, thou that liftest me up from the gates of death:
\p
\v 14 That I may show forth all thy praise in the gates of the daughter of Zion: I will rejoice in thy salvation.
\p
\v 15 The nations are sunk down in the pit \add that\add* they made: in the net which they hid is their own foot taken.
\p
\v 16 The LORD is known \add by\add* the judgment \add which\add* he executeth: the wicked is snared in the work of his own hands. Higgaion. Selah.
\p
\v 17 The wicked shall be turned into hell, \add and\add* all the nations that forget God.
\p
\v 18 For the needy shall not alway be forgotten: the expectation of the poor shall \add not\add* perish for ever.
\p
\v 19 Arise, O LORD; let not man prevail: let the nations be judged in thy sight.
\p
\v 20 Put them in fear, O LORD: \add that\add* the nations may know themselves \add to be but\add* men. Selah.
\c 10
\cl PSALM 10
\p
\v 1 ¶ Why standest thou afar off, O LORD? \add why\add* hidest thou \add thyself\add* in times of trouble?
\p
\v 2 The wicked in \add his\add* pride doth persecute the poor: let them be taken in the devices that they have imagined.
\p
\v 3 For the wicked boasteth of his heart’s desire, and blesseth the covetous, \add whom\add* the LORD abhorreth.
\p
\v 4 The wicked, through the pride of his countenance, will not seek \add after God:\add* God \add is\add* not in all his thoughts.
\p
\v 5 His ways are always grievous; thy judgments \add are\add* far above out of his sight: \add as for\add* all his enemies, he puffeth at them.
\p
\v 6 He hath said in his heart, I shall not be moved: for \add I shall\add* never \add be\add* in adversity.
\p
\v 7 His mouth is full of cursing and deceit and fraud: under his tongue \add is\add* mischief and vanity.
\p
\v 8 He sitteth in the lurking places of the villages: in the secret places doth he murder the innocent: his eyes are privily set against the poor.
\p
\v 9 He lieth in wait secretly as a lion in his den: he lieth in wait to catch the poor: he doth catch the poor, when he draweth him into his net.
\p
\v 10 He croucheth, \add and\add* humbleth himself, that the poor may fall by his strong ones.
\p
\v 11 He hath said in his heart, God hath forgotten: he hideth his face; he will never see \add it.\add*
\p
\v 12 Arise, O LORD; O God, lift up thine hand: forget not the humble.
\p
\v 13 Wherefore doth the wicked contemn God? he hath said in his heart, Thou wilt not require \add it.\add*
\p
\v 14 Thou hast seen \add it;\add* for thou beholdest mischief and spite, to requite \add it\add* with thy hand: the poor committeth himself unto thee; thou hast been the helper of the fatherless.
\p 
\v 15 Break thou the arm of the wicked and the evil \add man:\add* seek out his wickedness \add till\add* thou find none.
\p
\v 16 The LORD \add is\add* King for ever and ever: the nations are perished out of his land.
\p
\v 17 LORD, thou hast heard the desire of the humble: thou wilt prepare their heart, thou wilt cause thine ear to hear:
\p
\v 18 To judge the fatherless and the oppressed, that the man of the earth may no more oppress.
\c 11
\cl PSALM 11
\d To the chief Musician, \add A Psalm\add* of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ In the LORD put I my trust: how say ye to my soul, Flee \add as\add* a bird to your mountain?
\p
\v 2 For, lo, the wicked bend \add their\add* bow, they make ready their arrow upon the string, that they may privily shoot at the upright in heart.
\p
\v 3 If the foundations be destroyed, what can the righteous do?
\p
\v 4 The LORD \add is\add* in his holy temple, the LORD’S throne \add is\add* in heaven: his eyes behold, his eyelids try, the children of men.
\p
\v 5 The LORD trieth the righteous: but the wicked and him that loveth violence his soul hateth.
\p
\v 6 Upon the wicked he shall rain snares, fire and brimstone, and an horrible tempest: \add this shall be\add* the portion of their cup.
\p
\v 7 For righteous is the LORD, he loveth righteousness; his countenance doth behold the upright.
\c 12
\cl PSALM 12
\d To the chief Musician upon Sheminith, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ Help, LORD; for the godly man ceaseth; for the faithful fail from among the children of men.
\p
\v 2 They speak vanity every one with his neighbour: \add with\add* flattering lips \add and\add* with a double heart do they speak.
\p
\v 3 The LORD shall cut off all flattering lips, \add and\add* the tongue that speaketh proud things:
\p
\v 4 Who have said, With our tongue will we prevail; our lips \add are\add* our own: who \add is\add* lord over us?
\p 
\v 5 For the oppression of the poor, for the sighing of the needy, now will I arise, saith the LORD; I will set \add him\add* in safety \add from him that\add* puffeth at him.
\p
\v 6 The words of the LORD \add are\add* pure words: \add as\add* silver tried in a furnace of earth, purified seven times.
\p
\v 7 Thou shalt keep them, O LORD, thou shalt preserve them from this generation for ever.
\p
\v 8 The wicked walk on every side, when the vilest men are exalted.
\c 13
\cl PSALM 13
\d To the chief Musician, A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ How long wilt thou forget me, O LORD? for ever? how long wilt thou hide thy face from me?
\p
\v 2 How long shall I take counsel in my soul, \add having\add* sorrow in my heart daily? how long shall mine enemy be exalted over me?
\p
\v 3 Consider \add and\add* answer me, O LORD my God: lighten mine eyes, lest I sleep the \add sleep of\add* death;
\p
\v 4 Lest mine enemy say, I have prevailed against him; \add and\add* those that trouble me rejoice when I am moved.
\p
\v 5 But I have trusted in thy mercy; my heart shall rejoice in thy salvation.
\p
\v 6 I will sing unto the LORD, because he hath dealt bountifully with me.
\c 14
\cl PSALM 14
\d To the chief Musician, \add A Psalm\add* of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ The fool hath said in his heart, \add There is\add* no God. They are corrupt, they have done abominable works, \add there is\add* none that doeth good.
\p
\v 2 The LORD looked down from heaven upon the children of men, to see if there were any that did understand, \add and\add* seek God.
\p
\v 3 They are all gone aside, they are \add all\add* together become filthy: \add there is\add* none that doeth good, no, not one.
\p
\v 4 Have all the workers of iniquity no knowledge? who eat up my people \add as\add* they eat bread, and call not upon the LORD.
\p
\v 5 There were they in great fear: for God \add is\add* in the generation of the righteous.
\p
\v 6 Ye have shamed the counsel of the poor, because the LORD \add is\add* his refuge.
\p
\v 7 Oh that the salvation of Israel \add were come\add* out of Zion! when the LORD bringeth back the captivity of his people, Jacob shall rejoice, \add and\add* Israel shall be glad.
\c 15
\cl PSALM 15
\d A Psalm of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ LORD, who shall abide in thy tabernacle? who shall dwell in thy holy hill?
\p
\v 2 He that walketh uprightly, and worketh righteousness, and speaketh the truth in his heart.
\p
\v 3 \add He that\add* backbiteth not with his tongue, nor doeth evil to his neighbour, nor taketh up a reproach against his neighbour.
\p
\v 4 In whose eyes a vile person is contemned; but he honoureth them that fear the LORD. \add He that\add* sweareth to \add his own\add* hurt, and changeth not.
\p
\v 5 \add He that\add* putteth not out his money to usury, nor taketh reward against the innocent. He that doeth these \add things\add* shall never be moved.
\c 16
\cl PSALM 16
\d Michtam of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ Preserve me, O God: for in thee do I put my trust.
\p
\v 2 \add O my soul,\add* thou hast said unto the LORD, Thou \add art\add* my Lord: my goodness \add extendeth\add* not to thee;
\p
\v 3 \add But\add* to the saints that \add are\add* in the earth, and \add to\add* the excellent, in whom \add is\add* all my delight.
\p
\v 4 Their sorrows shall be multiplied \add that\add* give presents to another \add god:\add* their drink offerings of blood will I not offer, nor bear their names upon my lips.
\p
\v 5 The LORD \add is\add* the portion of mine inheritance and of my cup: thou maintainest my lot.
\p
\v 6 The lines are fallen unto me in pleasant \add places;\add* yea, I have a goodly heritage.
\p
\v 7 I will bless the LORD, who hath given me counsel: my reins also instruct me in the night seasons.
\p
\v 8 I have set the LORD always before me: because \add he is\add* at my right hand, I shall not be moved.
\p
\v 9 Therefore my heart is glad, and my glory rejoiceth: my flesh also shall rest in hope.
\p
\v 10 For thou wilt not leave my soul in hell; neither wilt thou suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.
\p
\v 11 Thou wilt show me the path of life: in thy presence \add is\add* fulness of joy; at thy right hand \add there are\add* pleasures for evermore.
\c 17
\cl PSALM 17
\d A Prayer of David.
\p
\v 1 ¶ Hear the right, O LORD, attend unto my cry, give ear unto my prayer, \add that goeth\add* not out of feigned lips.
\p
\v 2 Let my sentence come forth from thy presence; let thine eyes behold the things that are equal.
\p
\v 3 Thou hast proved mine heart; thou hast visited \add me\add* in the night; thou hast tried me, \add and\add* shalt find nothing; I am purposed \add that\add* my mouth shall not transgress.
\p
\v 4 Concerning the works of men, by the word of thy lips I have kept \add me from\add* the paths of the destroyer.
\p
\v 5 Thou hast held fast my goings in thy paths, \add that\add* my footsteps slip not.
\p
\v 6 I have called upon thee, for thou wilt answer me, O God: incline thine ear unto me, \add and hear\add* my speech.
\p
\v 7 Show thy marvellous lovingkindness, O thou that savest by thy right hand them that put their trust \add in thee\add* from those that rise up \add against them.\add*
\p
\v 8 Keep me as the apple of the eye, hide me under the shadow of thy wings,
\p
\v 9 From the wicked that oppress me, \add from\add* my deadly enemies, \add who\add* compass me about.
\p
\v 10 They are inclosed in their own fat: with their mouth they speak proudly.
\p
\v 11 They have now compassed us in our steps: they have set their eyes to bow us down to the earth;
\p
\v 12 Like as a lion \add that\add* is greedy of his prey, and as it were a young lion lurking in secret places.
\p
\v 13 Arise, O LORD, prevent him, cast him down: deliver my soul from the wicked, that \add is\add* thy sword:
\p
\v 14 From men \add that are\add* thy hand, O LORD, from men of the world, that \add have\add* their portion in \add this\add* life, and whose belly thou fillest with thy hid \add treasure:\add* they are full of children, and leave the rest of their \add substance\add* to their babes.
\p
\v 15 As for me, I will behold thy face in righteousness: I shall be satisfied, when I awake, with thy likeness.
\c 18
\cl PSALM 18
\d To the chief Musician, \add A Psalm\add* of David, the servant of the LORD, who spake unto the LORD the words of this song in the day \add that\add* the LORD delivered him from the hand of all his enemies, and from the hand of Saul: And he said,
\p
\v 1 ¶ I will love thee, O Lord, my strength.
\p
\v 2 The LORD \add is\add* my rock, and my fortress, and my deliverer; my God, my strength, in whom I will trust; my buckler, and the horn of my salvation, \add and\add* my high tower.
\p
\v 3 I will call upon the LORD, \add who is worthy\add* to be praised: so shall I be saved from mine enemies.
\p
\v 4 The sorrows of death compassed me, and the floods of ungodly men made me afraid.
\p
\v 5 The sorrows of hell compassed me about: the snares of death seized on me.
\p
\v 6 In my distress I called upon the LORD, and cried unto my God: he heard my voice out of his temple, and my cry came before him, \add even\add* into his ears.
\p
\v 7 Then the earth shook and trembled; the foundations also of the hills moved and were shaken, because he was wroth.
\p
\v 8 There went up a smoke out of his nostrils, and fire out of his mouth devoured: coals were kindled by it.
\p
\v 9 He bowed the heavens also, and came down: and thick darkness \add was\add* under his feet.
\p
\v 10 And he rode upon a cherub, and did fly: yea, he did fly upon the wings of the wind.
\p
\v 11 He made darkness his hiding place; his pavilion round about him \add were\add* dark waters \add and\add* thick clouds of the skies.
\p
\v 12 At the brightness \add that was\add* before him his thick clouds passed, hail \add stones\add* and coals of fire.
\p
\v 13 The LORD also thundered in the heavens, and the Highest gave his voice; hail \add stones\add* and coals of fire.
\p
\v 14 Yea, he sent out his arrows, and scattered them; and he shot out lightnings, and discomfited them.
\p
\v 15 Then the channels of waters were seen, and the foundations of the world were discovered at thy rebuke, O LORD, at the blast of the breath of thy nostrils.
\p
\v 16 He sent from above, he took me, he drew me out of many waters.
\p
\v 17 He delivered me from my strong enemy, and from them that hated me: for they were too strong for me.
\p
\v 18 They overcame me in the day of my calamity: but the LORD was my stay.
\p
\v 19 He brought me forth also into a large place; he delivered me, because he delighted in me.
\p
\v 20 The LORD rewarded me according to my righteousness; according to the cleanness of my hands hath he recompensed me.
\p
\v 21 For I have kept the ways of the LORD, and have not wickedly departed from my God.
\p
\v 22 For all his judgments \add were\add* before me, and I did not put away his statutes from me.
\p
\v 23 I was also upright before him, and I kept myself from mine iniquity.
\p
\v 24 Therefore hath the LORD recompensed me according to my righteousness, according to the cleanness of my hands in his eyesight.
\p
\v 25 With the merciful thou wilt show thyself merciful; with an upright man thou wilt show thyself upright;
\p
\v 26 With the pure thou wilt show thyself pure; and with the perverse thou wilt wrestle.
\p
\v 27 For thou wilt save the afflicted people; but wilt bring down high looks.
\p
